Perhaps it's a bit overkill using a fish-eye lens in the nest box.
Live long, learn long.
Since I've already made one with a "normal" lens, I should be clearer about this.
I'll install the second completed nest box over the weekend and post more information at that time.
Well, in 2015, the birds had faster internet than I did.
At least, that's the current plan.
Now there's a nest box, and it's connected to our home's wireless network.
Another nest box to get online will take some effort.
Okay, I hung the new nest box up during the day. This is what it looks like in the garden.
But let's take a step back for a moment. "What's inside it?" seems like no one has asked that.
The top part is an ESP32 camera board with a fish-eye lens camera and an infrared LED light that I removed from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box shape is unusual because the sides of the nest box can rotate. I bought it like that, and it couldn't be modified, so I had to design it according to this situation.
Since there's no power source in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 lithium-ion battery.
I didn't take a photo of the battery or charger, but this is a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box attached to the side of the nest box contains the battery.
It can run for approximately 4 hours after being fully charged.
I call this a "special feature". This way, the birds also have a bit of private space.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was good enough to support this device. The old access points I replaced last autumn certainly weren't.
However, the coverage area of the new access point is perfectly fine.
Now that's good, I was originally planning to put a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof, pointing downwards towards the garden.
If I were to build more birdhouses with cameras in the future, I might still do it this way, especially in areas farther away from the house.
Now, the camera has dropped offline for some reason I'm not yet clear about. It stopped working just an hour after sunset.
Perhaps it's due to insufficient light, as it stopped charging three hours before sunset.
Maybe half a day is not enough to fully charge it.
Let's see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have battery telemetry data yet. I might add this feature in future versions.
I wish I had a few more sensors.
I might need to add a battery too, at least theoretically, to let this thing run through the whole night.
Oh, and I need to change the lens.
The fisheye lens is a bit overkill.
But I have already browsed the components on Digikey, so I might just custom-design a PCB for this specific situation.
Or maybe not. We'll see later.
And it's still offline.
Great.
From the orientation of the solar panels installed on the house, the actual time that receives sunlight is only about 90 minutes.
Wait for another hour or two to see if it does anything (or nothing).
Still offline.
Sigh, nothing is ever easy.
It turns out that the 5V line and GND line on the USB-C splitter I used to connect the battery charger were printed backwards on the silk screen.
After swapping the lines, the charging indicator light turned on.
The ESP didn't come online immediately, so let's wait for a few minutes.
An hour passed, and it was still offline.
It seems it got stuck in a reboot loop, triggering the watchdog reset function.
It looks like this board is junk. I've ordered a bigger one, hoping it will solve the problem.
Let's see what I found in my workshop.
This is a 24-volt solar panel. Unfortunately, the sun is too low (and there's also a tree blocking it), and as soon as I added a load, the voltage dropped significantly.
It seems I'll have to wait until tomorrow to know if this solar panel is sufficient or if I need the better-performing one that I ordered.
The information on Amazon shows that this solar panel was purchased in 2021, with a maximum output of 12 volts and 1.2 amps.
So, either this solar panel is faulty, or my multimeter is faulty, or they've changed the product page.
Hi everyone, good news!
They changed the product page, and the one I have is faulty.
The titles of both old and new product pages call it a 12-volt 10-watt solar panel.
This is why I didn't delete the old emails.
Hey, look: it regained connection about an hour ago, but only for about half a minute.
Perhaps the solar panel charged the battery a bit, just enough to run for 38 seconds. This time should be around two and a half hours.
Guess what: it's a rainy day today! So, I'm not sure if that (possibly broken) solar panel will be able to generate enough power to work.
Let's wait and see.
Latest update: the new solar panel is installed and it looks like it's working normally now.
Maybe the sun will set and it will shut down, but let's wait and see.
Interestingly, I'm using Home Assistant's ping functionality to monitor if it's online.
Average round-trip time is 102 milliseconds. It's neither good nor bad.
